english:
  title: A Biography of Baek
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Baek—whose given name was Rin—hailed from Seorim, a friend of my youth. When my father, Master Gajeong, served as examiner in the gwageo of that fateful year, Baek rose through the second tier of candidates. Thus we became schoolmates. Seorim and our Hansan lay adjacent, fields interlocking like a dog's teeth, our homes nearly touching. In those unbound days of youth, we played together and read books side by side at Sungjeong Temple—true classmates. Now, the monk Naezan of the Cheontae order loves to keep company with scholars and delights in reciting the poems of Dongpo. The scholars flock to hear his words until the hall overflows. Among them, the most noble spirits formed an association to demonstrate their faith, and Baek became its steward. Thus we became fellow travelers in purpose. How could one claim not to know Baek? To know a man and yet leave his story untold to posterity—this is not the heart of a virtuous person.

    His father bore the name Hamjeong. In service to the Bureau of Court Attendants, he upheld propriety whenever among others. Should any of the various administrators transgress the law or jest with crude words, he would bristle with indignation, step back, and declare: "My father named me Hamjeong—meaning uprightness. How could I ever allow myself the slightest deviation?" The administrators grew to revere him over time. He rose to become Chamberlain of the Gate of Harmonious Courtesy. His mother was of the Kim clan from Sangju, daughter of one Intong who served as Treasury Official. Baek had one younger brother named Seo, who advanced through the Bureau of Evaluators to become Senior Secretary of the Ministry of Officials, and now holds office with a reputation for capability. Baek married the daughter of an official Ki, named Yu, and fathered one daughter who married into another noble house. He later took a second wife, daughter of the official Jeong, but had no sons.

    Baek possessed a brilliance of mind and strength of memory unmatched in recent times. When we lodged together at a temple in Hyeonju, we once wagered on recitation of our studies. Before midday, Baek had finished what took me until nightfall to complete. Over a year later, sharing lodgings at a Seorim temple, we lay in darkness without lamp and played chess by voice alone. The next morning, when we reviewed the board, Baek had not misplaced a single piece, while I had committed errors in two places. Such incidents were numerous, though I shall not recount them all—yet these suffice to reveal Baek's nature.

    Baek possessed an appetite prodigious beyond measure, consuming the portion of two men without feeling sated. He was also possessed of great strength—even those who boasted of their own prowess dared not challenge him. In his writing, his spirit flowed like an endless rainbow, a force he could scarcely contain. His calligraphy, too, bore no vulgarity. He once inscribed the burial inscription for my grandmother's hall, and my father surely found merit in his brushwork.

    In the autumn of that year marked Eulmi, as I served in the Hall of Worthies, preparing to return home the following spring, we spent one night in conversation. Though Baek's sojourn abroad weighed heavily upon him, his spirit remained undimmed. He harbored ambitions for advancement and honor. Yet in the end, he accomplished nothing and was buried in foreign soil at Yanjing. Alas, what sorrow!
  footnotes:
    - 'Gwageo (科擧): The civil service examination system through which officials were recruited in classical East Asia.'
    - 'Dongpo: Su Shi (1037-1101), the renowned Song Dynasty poet and statesman, greatly admired in Korea.'
    - 'Hamjeong (咸正): The name carries the meaning of ''perfect uprightness'' or ''perfect rectitude.'''
    - 'Yanjing: The classical name for Beijing, indicating Baek died while serving or traveling in the Yuan court.'
